# YugabyteDB query-layer retries

PostgreSQL never retries a failed statement on its own. Under REPEATABLE
READ / SERIALIZABLE, a serialization failure (SQLSTATE 40001) is returned
to the client for the application to handle. Under READ COMMITTED, PG
does not raise the error at all: the executor resolves the conflict in
place via `EvalPlanQual`, re-reading just the conflicting rows. And
because PG is single-node with one consistent snapshot, no read is ever
"maybe stale, try again."

YugabyteDB runs the PG query layer over a distributed storage engine
that bounds clock skew rather than eliminating it. Two things follow:
reads in the clock-uncertainty window can hit a **read restart** error
that single-node PG never produces; and RC conflicts surface at the
query layer rather than being absorbed in the executor.

Surfacing either as-is would break PG compatibility -- apps never expect
read restarts, and under RC they don't expect serialization failures. YB
transparently retries these at the query layer when the retry is safe.

## Where the database retries (orientation map)

| # | Retry | Where |
|---|-------|-------|
| 1 | Schema / catalog cache mismatch | `YBPrepareCacheRefreshIfNeeded` (postgres.c) |
| 2 | Serialization errors (read restart / conflict / deadlock / aborted) | `yb_is_retry_possible` + `yb_exec_query_wrapper` (postgres.c) |
| 3 | RPC retries, query -> storage | pggate / docdb |
| 4 | Wait-queue retries | docdb wait queues |
| 5 | Storage-layer read-restart retries | docdb |
| 6 | Other ad-hoc retries | various |

---

## Retrying serialization errors

`yb_is_retry_possible` gates whether an error is retriable;
`yb_exec_query_wrapper` is the loop.

### Where the retry sits

The loop wraps `exec_simple_query` (simple protocol `Q`) and
`exec_execute_message` (extended-protocol Execute). Parse and Bind are
not replayed; the redo reuses the already-bound portal, so portal state
must survive across attempts.

### Statement retry vs. transaction retry

- **Statement retry** rolls back to an internal sub-transaction taken
  before the statement (`RollbackAndReleaseCurrentSubTransaction`) and
  re-runs it. RC path.
- **Transaction retry** restarts the whole transaction surgically using
  (`YBCRestartWriteTransaction()`, plus a read-point reset for read
  restarts). RR/SR path.

### Which statements are retried

See the "Supported retries" comment block in `yb_is_retry_possible`
(postgres.c) for the per-isolation, per-error-kind matrix. The two
opt-in GUCs -- `yb_extra_commands_to_retry` (top level) and
`yb_extra_commands_to_retry_in_proc` (inside CALL/DO bodies) -- widen
that set.

One caveat worth flagging here: read restart on DDL was never retried
by default, even under RC. The DDL retry path was never validated for
read restarts.

### When a retry is not safe (and hence blocked)

The retry assumes the failed statement can be wound back and re-run.
Common reasons that doesn't hold:

1. **Pinned snapshot (RR/SR).** A transaction retry adopts a new read
   point, which is only sound before the transaction has externalized
   data from the snapshot -- i.e. only for the first statement.
2. **The statement's own output has started flushing.** Re-emitting
   result rows would duplicate any already flushed to the client, so
   the retry needs the output buffer still intact (the buffer is
   discarded before re-execution so the redo starts clean).
3. **Side effects that rollback cannot undo.** A retry relies on
   savepoint/transaction rollback to erase the failed attempt;
   anything escaping that rollback -- in storage, the query layer, or
   elsewhere -- gets double-applied on redo. COPY is the canonical
   example: it commits rows in batches, so a restart re-inserts the
   committed prefix.

### Async (batched) execution

In the extended protocol, commands pipeline before `Sync` and output
isn't flushed until `Sync`, so within a batch `YBIsDataSent` and
`YBIsDataSentForCurrQuery` stay false even after mutations execute.
Sync execution got the "only first command can retry" restriction for
free from `YBIsDataSent` flipping on flush; async doesn't, so:

    if (YbIsBatchedExecution() && GetCurrentCommandId(false) > FirstCommandId)
        return false;

Without this, retrying a later command would lose earlier ones in the
batch -- they aren't recorded for replay, so undoing them deletes them
from the transaction.
